For calculating this integral we use substitution.

\begin{align*}\int_{-1}^0\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x}}dx = \int_{-1}^0(1-x)^{-\frac12}dx.\end{align*}

We define \emph{u}=1-\emph{x}, \emph{du}=-\emph{dx}. The new limits of
the integral are \emph{u}(-1)=1-(-1)=2 and \emph{u}(0)=1-0=1. Hence

\begin{align*}\int_2^1u^{-\frac12}(-du) = \int_1^2u^{-\frac12}du = \left[2u^{\frac12}\right]_1^2 = 2(\sqrt2-1).\end{align*}
